      "title": "Cambridge Analytica is shutting down",
      "body": "Political data firm Cambridge Analytica is shutting down after the Facebook privacy debacle.\n\nCambridge Analytica was at the center of a data privacy firestorm involving its collection of up to 87 million Facebook users' data and its use of the data for political campaigns, such as Donald Trump's 2016 presidential campaign. The revelations of the use of the data without user permission -- bolstered by a former Cambridge Analytica employee turned whistleblower -- led to Facebook executives, including CEO Mark Zuckerberg, testifying in front of the U.S. Congress and the British Parliament.\n\nWednesday, Cambridge Analytica announced it will cease all operations and begin bankruptcy proceedings for its U.S. operations with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court for the Southern District of New York.\n\nCambridge Analytica shut down offices in London, New York City and Washington, D.C. on Wednesday, the Wall Street Journal reported before the company confirmed it. Its employees were immediately ordered to turn in their computers, according the Journal said.\n\nCambridge Analytica said its demise stemmed from \"numerous unfounded accusations,\" and that it was painted as a villain by the media for \"activities that are not only legal, but also widely accepted as a standard component of online advertising in both the political and commercial arenas.\"\n\n\"Despite Cambridge Analytica's unwavering confidence that its employees have acted ethically and lawfully... the siege of media coverage has driven away virtually all of the Company's customers and suppliers,\" the company said in its announcement. \"As a result, it has been determined that it is no longer viable to continue operating the business, which left Cambridge Analytica with no realistic alternative to placing the Company into administration.\"\n\nSCL Group, the parent company of Cambridge Analytica, decided to pull the plug after the firm began to lose multiple clients after the Facebook fallout, according to the Journal.\n\nNigel Oakes, the founder of SCL Group, Cambridge Analytica's British affiliate, said both companies were closing down, the Journal reported.\n\nCambridge Analytica's former CEO, Alexander Nix, was suspended in March after the British television channel Channel 4 caught Nix saying in an undercover interview that his company used honey traps, bribes and prostitutes to influence elections across the globe. In April, the company said it committed no wrongdoing in harvesting Facebook user data.\n\n\"The company has been portrayed as some Bond villain,\" said company spokesman Clarence Mitchell in a press conference. \"Cambridge Analytica is no Bond villain.\"\n\nCambridge Analytica did not immediately respond to an email request and multiple phone calls to both its commercial and political departments from this news organization.",
