      "url": "https://www.telegraphindia.com/world/mps-react-with-fury-over-ca-bankruptcy-227956",
      "title": "MPs react with fury over CA bankruptcy",
      "body": "London: MPs in Britain have reacted with fury to the news that scandal hit Cambridge Analytica has shut down after declaring itself bankrupt in an alleged attempt to prevent an investigation into how it exploited data harvested from 87 million Facebook users.\n\nDamian Collins, a Tory MP who is chairman of the Commons select committee for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, tweeted: \"Cambridge Analytica and (its parent company) SCL Group cannot be allowed to delete their data history by closing.\"\n\n\"The investigations into their work are vital,\" he insisted. Collins has repeated a request for Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg to appear before his committee, claiming evidence provided by the firm's chief technology officer Mike Schroepfer sent in his place last week \"failed to answer fully\" almost 40 questions.\n\nCambridge Analytica, a US-firm once retained by Facebook, shut down its operations on Wednesday citing loss of business and, as a symbolic gesture, even removed its nameplate from the central London offices that it had occupied.\n\nBut British MPs see all this as a ruse to frustrate an investigation into its activities. Cambridge Analytica denies wrongdoing but has been accused of interfering in the US elections and the Brexit referendum in 2016.\n\nHowever, nothing illegal has been found about the work it apparently did for the Congress Party in India.\n\nCollins told the BBC that Cambridge Analytica would not be allowed to escape the consequences of any illegal activities.\n\n\"We've got to make sure this isn't at attempt to run and hide, that these companies are not closing down to try to avoid them being rigorously investigated over the allegations that are being made against them,\" he said.\n\nHe was backed by Labour MP Mary Creagh, who reacted angrily to Cambridge Analytica's decision to declare itself bankrupt. \"Outrageous,\" she summed up. \"Insolvency used to cover up illegality.\"\n\nThe Information Commissioner's Office also served notice that Cambridge Analytica would be held to account.\n\nIt said: \"The ICO has been investigating the SCL Group and Cambridge Analytica as part of a wider investigation into the use of personal data and analytics by political campaigns, social media companies and others. We will be examining closely the details of the announcements of the winding down of Cambridge Analytica and the status of its parent company.\n\n\"The ICO will continue its civil and criminal investigations and will seek to pursue individuals and directors as appropriate and necessary even where companies may no longer be operating.\n\n\"We will also monitor closely any successor companies using our powers to audit and inspect, to ensure the public is safeguarded.\"\n\nOn Wednesday, Cambridge Analytica took everyone by surprise by announcing it was putting itself out of business. The company said in a statement: \"Over the past several months, Cambridge Analytica has been the subject of numerous unfounded accusations and, despite the company's efforts to correct the record, has been vilified for activities that are not only legal, but also widely accepted as a standard component of online advertising in both the political and commercial arenas.\n\n\"Despite Cambridge Analytica's unwavering confidence that its employees have acted ethically and lawfully... the siege of media coverage has driven away virtually all of the company's customers and suppliers.\n\n\"As a result, it has been determined that it is no longer viable to continue operating the business, which left Cambridge Analytica with no realistic alternative to placing the company into administration.\"",
